EZEK_CONTEXT = {
  "1": {
    "1": "<p>Ezekiel was a priest who was deported to Babylon in the first deportation (597 BCE) and received his call-vision in 593 BCE by the Chebar canal in Babylonia ('the thirtieth year', 1:1 — possibly his own thirtieth year, the age for priestly service). He prophesied to the exilic community ca. 593-571 BCE. His priestly background shapes his theology: the book is preoccupied with divine glory (<em>kavod</em>), the departure of the Shekinah from the temple (chs. 8-11), and its eschatological return (chs. 40-48). The merkabah vision (ch. 1) was the most influential single vision in subsequent Jewish mysticism — the Hekhalot literature built an entire tradition of heavenly ascent around it. The four living creatures (lion, ox, eagle, human) reappear in Irenaeus's identification of the four Gospel symbols.</p>"
  },
  "37": {
    "1": "<p>The valley of dry bones vision (37:1-14) is addressed to the exilic community that had concluded 'our bones are dried up, our hope is lost, we are indeed cut off' (v. 11). The corporate resurrection metaphor — national restoration envisioned as bodily resurrection — uses the imagery of physical resurrection for Israel's return from exile. This is not a straightforward prophecy of individual eschatological resurrection (though the same imagery is applied there in Isa 26:19; Dan 12:2), but a bold use of resurrection as the metaphor for what only divine creative power could accomplish for the exiled nation. The NT develops the resurrection-from-exile typology: Christ's resurrection is both personal and the beginning of the great return-from-death that Ezekiel envisioned.</p>"
  }
}

EZEK_CHRIST = {
  "18": {
    "1": "<p>A structural note: The divine word formula opens the oracle of individual accountability. Christ is the Word who takes the covenant&rsquo;s moral demand personally — he does not merely transmit commands but embodies them. &ldquo;In him there is no sin&rdquo; (1 John 3:5) — he alone of all human beings meets the standard that ch. 18 requires, and he meets it on behalf of those who cannot.</p>",
    "2": "<p>A pattern: The proverb &ldquo;the fathers ate sour grapes and the children&rsquo;s teeth are set on edge&rdquo; encodes the theology of inherited guilt from which Christ&rsquo;s redemption liberates. Paul&rsquo;s parallel: &ldquo;in Adam all die&rdquo; (1 Cor 15:22) — the original inherited guilt. Christ enters the inherited-guilt condition (&ldquo;born of a woman, born under the law,&rdquo; Gal 4:4) to liberate those who are trapped in it, replacing the proverb of death in Adam with the proverb of life in Christ.</p>",
    "3": "<p>A direct revelation: &ldquo;As I live, declares the Lord GOD, you shall have no more occasion to use this proverb.&rdquo; YHWH abolishes the proverb of inherited guilt by decree. Christ is the one through whom the decree is enacted: &ldquo;there is therefore now no condemnation for those who are in Christ Jesus&rdquo; (Rom 8:1). The proverb of inherited death is silenced by the new covenant word of individual justification through faith in Christ.</p>",
    "4": "<p>A direct revelation: &ldquo;Every person belongs to me — the parent and the child alike: the person who sins is the one who will die.&rdquo; This verse establishes the principle that makes Christ&rsquo;s substitution both necessary and possible. Christ belongs to YHWH as the righteous Son — he is the one person who does not die for his own sin. His voluntary death in the place of sinners is the supreme reversal of the principle: the sinless person dies so that the sinful person need not. &ldquo;He made him to be sin who knew no sin, so that in him we might become the righteousness of God&rdquo; (2 Cor 5:21).</p>",
    "5": "<p>A pattern: The righteous man who does what is &ldquo;lawful and right&rdquo; is the legal ideal of the covenant. Christ is the only person who perfectly embodies this ideal — the truly righteous man of Ezekiel&rsquo;s taxonomy, walking in all the statutes and keeping all the ordinances (vv. 5-9). His perfect righteousness, credited to believers through faith, is the ground of justification (Rom 5:19: &ldquo;by the one man&rsquo;s obedience the many will be made righteous&rdquo;).</p>",
    "6": "<p>A pattern: The righteous man&rsquo;s abstinence from mountain-shrine eating, idolatry, and sexual violation represents the comprehensive covenant faithfulness that Jesus perfectly embodied. Jesus ate with sinners and tax collectors but never compromised with idolatry; he engaged women in public conversation but never violated sexual boundaries. The righteous-man portrait in vv. 6-9 is Christological: it describes the covenant fidelity that Christ alone fulfills completely.</p>",
    "7": "<p>A pattern: The righteous man&rsquo;s social ethics — returning the pledge, not robbing, feeding the hungry, clothing the naked — are exactly the ethics Christ both teaches and practices. The Sermon on the Mount extends these ethics; Jesus&rsquo;s parable of the sheep and goats (Matt 25:31-46) makes the feeding/clothing of the vulnerable the criterion of judgment. Christ fulfills the righteous man&rsquo;s social ethics and embodies them as the standard of the kingdom.</p>",
    "8": "<p>A pattern: Not lending at interest, rendering honest judgment — the financial and judicial ethics of the righteous man. Christ overturns the money-changers&rsquo; tables in the temple (Matt 21:12-13), a prophetic protest against economic exploitation in the sacred precincts. His &ldquo;render to Caesar what is Caesar&rsquo;s, and to God what is God&rsquo;s&rdquo; (Matt 22:21) is the quintessential honest-judgment statement on the justice of temporal and divine claims.</p>",
    "9": "<p>A direct revelation: &ldquo;He has walked in my statutes and kept my ordinances faithfully — he is just; he shall surely live.&rdquo; This verdict — &ldquo;he shall surely live&rdquo; — is pronounced over the righteous man who fulfills the covenant. Christ alone perfectly qualifies for this verdict; his resurrection is its definitive pronouncement. The resurrection is YHWH&rsquo;s own verdict of &ldquo;surely live&rdquo; pronounced over the one who walked in all the divine statutes — and through justification, this verdict is extended to all who are in him (Rom 4:25: &ldquo;he was raised for our justification&rdquo;).</p>",
    "10": "<p>A structural note: The wicked son of a righteous father is the anti-type of Christ&rsquo;s relationship to the Father. Where the rebellious son inverts the father&rsquo;s righteousness, Christ perfectly reflects the Father&rsquo;s character: &ldquo;whoever has seen me has seen the Father&rdquo; (John 14:9). The possibility of the wicked son highlights by contrast the unique faithfulness of the Son who always does what pleases the Father (John 8:29).</p>",
    "11": "<p>A structural note: The wicked son eats at mountain shrines and defiles his neighbor&rsquo;s wife — the two signature covenant violations (idolatry and sexual immorality) that Jesus explicitly identifies as heart-level sins (Matt 5:28: looking with lust is adultery in the heart; Matt 6:24: serving two masters is practical idolatry). Christ addresses the inner-life roots that produce the wicked son&rsquo;s external covenant violations.</p>",
    "12": "<p>A structural note: The wicked son oppresses the poor and needy — the exact opposite of the righteous man&rsquo;s social ethics. Jesus announces his mission as good news to the poor (Luke 4:18), releasing the oppressed. The socioeconomic reversal of the kingdom (the poor are blessed, the rich are warned — Luke 6:20-26) is the eschatological reversal of the wicked-son pattern.</p>",
    "13": "<p>A structural note: &ldquo;His blood is upon his own head&rdquo; — the principle of self-incurred blood-guilt for covenant violation. On the cross, the crowd says &ldquo;his blood be on us and on our children&rdquo; (Matt 27:25) — a self-cursing formula. But Christ&rsquo;s blood, rather than remaining on those who bear it, is the blood that cleanses: &ldquo;the blood of Jesus his Son cleanses us from all sin&rdquo; (1 John 1:7). The curse-blood formula is reversed by the atonement.</p>",
    "14": "<p>A pattern: The righteous grandson who sees the father&rsquo;s sins and does not repeat them represents moral self-determination independent of family pattern. Christ comes from a lineage of sinners (the genealogy of Matt 1 includes Rahab, Ruth, Bathsheba, and the Babylonian deportation), but his righteousness is his own — not derived from ancestral purity. He is &ldquo;holy, blameless, unstained, separated from sinners&rdquo; (Heb 7:26) despite his fully human genealogy.</p>",
    "15": "<p>A structural note: The righteous grandson&rsquo;s catalog of virtues mirrors the righteous grandfather&rsquo;s, establishing that covenant faithfulness is individually chosen, not inherited. Christ&rsquo;s righteousness is the supreme instance of this principle: he chose the Father&rsquo;s will at every point (Gethsemane: &ldquo;not my will, but yours be done,&rdquo; Luke 22:42), making his righteousness a fully willed act, not a mechanical necessity.</p>",
    "16": "<p>A structural note: The righteous grandson does not withhold the pledge and feeds the hungry — positive enactments of covenant solidarity that mirror Christ&rsquo;s provision. The multiplication of loaves (Matt 14:19-21), the Cana wine (John 2:1-11), and the post-resurrection breakfast on the shore (John 21:9-13) are Christ&rsquo;s feeding-the-hungry enacted on behalf of those who hunger for life, not merely bread.</p>",
    "17": "<p>A direct revelation: &ldquo;He shall not die for his father&rsquo;s iniquity; he shall surely live.&rdquo; The verdict of life over the righteous regardless of ancestral sin is the covenantal principle that Christ enacts universally. In Christ, the believer does not die for Adam&rsquo;s iniquity but lives by Christ&rsquo;s righteousness: &ldquo;for as by a man came death, by a man has come also the resurrection of the dead. For as in Adam all die, so also in Christ shall all be made alive&rdquo; (1 Cor 15:21-22).</p>",
    "18": "<p>A structural note: The wicked father dies in his own iniquity, with no cover from the son&rsquo;s righteousness. Christ&rsquo;s righteousness, however, does cover the guilty — but only on the basis of personal faith-union, not on the basis of family relationship. The difference between Ezekiel&rsquo;s verdict (no coverage) and the gospel (coverage through faith in Christ) is not a contradiction but a deepening: Christ creates the possibility that the father can be covered if he also turns.</p>",
    "19": "<p>A structural note: The people&rsquo;s objection — why does the son not bear the father&rsquo;s iniquity? — reveals the expectation that family solidarity runs both ways. Christ voluntarily accepts the iniquity he was under no moral obligation to bear: &ldquo;he was pierced for our transgressions, crushed for our iniquities&rdquo; (Isa 53:5). The substitution is not an application of Ezekiel&rsquo;s principle but its voluntary surpassing: the sinless Son bears what the son of this chapter is released from.</p>",
    "20": "<p>A direct revelation: &ldquo;The person who sins is the one who will die. The son will not bear the iniquity of the father.&rdquo; This is the principle Christ inverts in the atonement — not by violating the moral law but by fulfilling it from the inside. As the only truly righteous Son, he had the moral capital to give himself for others: &ldquo;for our sake he made him to be sin who knew no sin&rdquo; (2 Cor 5:21). The one who had no iniquity to die for became the one who died for all iniquity.</p>",
    "21": "<p>A direct revelation: &ldquo;If the wicked man turns from all his sins... he will surely live.&rdquo; This verse is the OT statement of the gospel: repentance from sin, keeping YHWH&rsquo;s statutes, life as the result. Christ announces the same gospel: &ldquo;repent and believe in the gospel&rdquo; (Mark 1:15); &ldquo;the Son of Man came to seek and to save the lost&rdquo; (Luke 19:10). The difference in the NT is that the statutes-keeping is enabled by the Spirit and credited through Christ&rsquo;s perfect righteousness, not by the sinner&rsquo;s own performance.</p>",
    "22": "<p>A direct revelation: &ldquo;All the transgressions he has committed will not be held against him.&rdquo; This is Ezekiel&rsquo;s anticipation of the NT doctrine of justification: transgressions are not counted against the one who turns. Paul makes the same point in the language of imputation (Rom 4:7-8, citing Ps 32:1-2: &ldquo;blessed is the man against whom the Lord will not count his sin&rdquo;). The non-counting of transgressions is possible only because they are counted against Christ instead.</p>",
    "23": "<p>A direct revelation: &ldquo;Do I have any pleasure in the death of the wicked? Is it not rather that he should turn from his ways and live?&rdquo; YHWH&rsquo;s desire is for repentance and life, not death and judgment. This is the theological foundation of the incarnation: the God who takes no pleasure in the death of the wicked sends his Son so that &ldquo;whoever believes in him should not perish but have eternal life&rdquo; (John 3:16). &ldquo;God is patient toward you, not wishing that any should perish, but that all should reach repentance&rdquo; (2 Pet 3:9) — Ezekiel&rsquo;s desire expressed as the divine motive for the cross.</p>",
    "24": "<p>A structural note: The righteous person who turns to wickedness dies in their iniquity. The possibility of apostasy is a serious NT concern as well (Heb 6:4-6; 10:26-31). Christ&rsquo;s warning in the Gospels about those who hear the word but fall away (the parable of the sower, Mark 4:5-6, 16-17) is Ezekiel&rsquo;s conversion-principle applied to the kingdom context: the good news received does not guarantee perseverance apart from continued faith.</p>",
    "25": "<p>A structural note: The complaint &ldquo;the way of the Lord is not fair&rdquo; reflects the persistent human objection to divine moral accounting. Christ engages this objection in the parable of the laborers (Matt 20:1-16): &ldquo;or do you begrudge my generosity? So the last will be first, and the first last.&rdquo; YHWH&rsquo;s ways appear unfair to those who expect automatic reward for accumulated moral credit — but Christ&rsquo;s grace is even more radical than Ezekiel&rsquo;s justice.</p>",
    "26": "<p>A structural note: The righteous person who turns and dies in their iniquity — the symmetric verdict. Christ&rsquo;s letter to the church at Ephesus (Rev 2:4-5) applies the same logic: &ldquo;you have abandoned the love you had at first. Remember therefore from where you have fallen; repent, and do the works you did at first. If not, I will come to you and remove your lampstand from its place.&rdquo; The possibility of losing what was previously held is the NT form of this warning.</p>",
    "27": "<p>A direct revelation: &ldquo;When a wicked person turns from the wickedness they committed and does what is lawful and right, they will save their own life.&rdquo; The life-saving dynamic of repentance points forward to Christ&rsquo;s parable of the prodigal son: &ldquo;and he arose and came to his father&rdquo; (Luke 15:20). The turn toward righteousness that Ezekiel describes is, in the NT, a turn toward the Father through Christ, whose righteousness provides the ground of the restored standing.</p>",
    "28": "<p>A structural note: &ldquo;Because he considered his ways and turned from all the transgressions he committed.&rdquo; The double movement of moral reflection and turning is the structure of NT repentance. Paul&rsquo;s description of the Corinthians&rsquo; repentance uses the same structure: &ldquo;what earnestness this godly grief has produced in you, what eagerness to clear yourselves, what indignation, what fear, what longing, what zeal, what punishment!&rdquo; (2 Cor 7:11). Christ&rsquo;s call to repentance includes both the considering (&ldquo;count the cost,&rdquo; Luke 14:28) and the turning.</p>",
    "29": "<p>A structural note: The repeated complaint &ldquo;the way of the Lord is not fair&rdquo; followed by YHWH&rsquo;s counter — &ldquo;are not your ways the ones that are unfair?&rdquo; — is the moral accountability reversal that Christ enacts in his ministry. Jesus&rsquo;s interlocutors consistently find his moral accounting surprising: the workers hired last are paid the same (Matt 20:12), the younger son is celebrated while the elder sulks (Luke 15:28-30). YHWH&rsquo;s ways appear unfair only to those still calculating in terms of merit.</p>",
    "30": "<p>A direct revelation: &ldquo;Repent and turn from all your transgressions, so that iniquity will not be your downfall.&rdquo; This is the OT form of the gospel command. Christ&rsquo;s first public word is &ldquo;repent, for the kingdom of heaven is at hand&rdquo; (Matt 4:17) — the same imperative, now accompanied by the arrival of the one who makes repentance not merely obligatory but possible and fruitful. The &ldquo;stumbling block&rdquo; (<em>mikshol</em>) of iniquity that Ezekiel warns against is what Christ removes: &ldquo;blessed is the one who is not offended by me&rdquo; (Matt 11:6).</p>",
    "31": "<p>A direct revelation: &ldquo;Make yourselves a new heart and a new spirit — for why should you die, O house of Israel?&rdquo; The command to make a new heart and spirit points to the new covenant promise of Ezek 36:26 where YHWH provides what he here commands. Christ is the mediator of the new covenant (Heb 9:15) through whom both the command and the provision are fulfilled: &ldquo;unless one is born again he cannot see the kingdom of God&rdquo; (John 3:3) — the new heart is the new birth from above, accomplished through the Spirit sent by the risen Christ.</p>",
    "32": "<p>A direct revelation: &ldquo;I have no pleasure in the death of anyone who dies, declares the Lord GOD. Therefore turn and live!&rdquo; The final verse of ch. 18 is the OT&rsquo;s most concentrated expression of the gospel invitation. The two-word Hebrew command <em>shuvu vichyu</em> (turn and live) is the gospel in miniature. John 3:16 expands it: the God who takes no pleasure in the death of sinners gives his Son so that turning toward him brings eternal life rather than the death that sin earns. &ldquo;Turn and live&rdquo; becomes &ldquo;believe and live&rdquo; when the Son is revealed as the object of turning.</p>"
  },
  "19": {
    "1": "<p>A pattern: &ldquo;Raise up a lament for the princes of Israel.&rdquo; Ezekiel the prophet is commanded to lament over Israel&rsquo;s failed kings. Christ himself laments over Jerusalem and its leadership: &ldquo;O Jerusalem, Jerusalem, the city that kills the prophets and stones those sent to her! How often would I have gathered your children together as a hen gathers her brood, and you were not willing&rdquo; (Matt 23:37). The prophetic lament over Israel&rsquo;s failed shepherds (chs. 19, 34) reaches its fullest expression in Christ&rsquo;s tears over the city (Luke 19:41).</p>",
    "2": "<p>A type: The lioness who bears royal cubs &ldquo;among lions&rdquo; — Judah as a lioness — points forward to the Davidic promise that culminates in Christ. Gen 49:9-10 (&ldquo;Judah is a lion&rsquo;s cub... the scepter shall not depart from Judah&rdquo;) is fulfilled in &ldquo;the Lion of the tribe of Judah, the Root of David&rdquo; who has conquered (Rev 5:5). Where the lioness&rsquo;s cubs are taken captive and the royal line apparently ends, Christ is the cub who cannot be captured and whose kingdom cannot end (Luke 1:33).</p>",
    "3": "<p>A structural note: The first cub &ldquo;learned to catch prey and devoured men&rdquo; — the predatory kingship that characterizes Israel&rsquo;s failed rulers. Christ comes as the anti-predatory king: &ldquo;the Son of Man came not to be served but to serve, and to give his life as a ransom for many&rdquo; (Mark 10:45). The lions who devour men are replaced by the Shepherd-King who lays down his life for the flock.</p>",
    "4": "<p>A pattern: &ldquo;He was caught in their pit; they brought him in chains to the land of Egypt.&rdquo; The captured and chained king is the type of Israel&rsquo;s humiliated rulers. Christ is the king who surrendered himself to captors: &ldquo;do you think I cannot call on my Father, and he will at once put at my disposal more than twelve legions of angels?&rdquo; (Matt 26:53). He was bound and taken away not by enemies&rsquo; power but by his own voluntary submission — the captured king who could not be held (Acts 2:24: &ldquo;God raised him up, loosing the pangs of death, because it was not possible for him to be held by it&rdquo;).</p>",
    "5": "<p>A structural note: &ldquo;When she saw that her hope was gone and her waiting had come to nothing, she took another of her cubs.&rdquo; The disappointed hope and renewed attempt is the pattern of Israel&rsquo;s persistent seeking of the messianic king through the Davidic line — each king disappointing, each captivity crushing the hope, yet the hope renewed. The final renewal of this hope comes not through another failed cub but through the resurrection: &ldquo;I had hoped that he was the one to redeem Israel&rdquo; (Luke 24:21) is transformed into &ldquo;the Lord has risen indeed&rdquo; (Luke 24:34).</p>",
    "6": "<p>A structural note: The second cub also &ldquo;learned to catch prey and devoured men&rdquo; — the pattern of predatory kingship repeating across generations. The repeated failure of Israel&rsquo;s kings creates the vacuum that Christ fills: where every human king devoured, the king who gave himself to be devoured for others establishes a radically different kingdom. &ldquo;I am the good shepherd; the good shepherd lays down his life for the sheep&rdquo; (John 10:11).</p>",
    "7": "<p>A structural note: &ldquo;He ravaged their strongholds and laid waste their cities.&rdquo; The destructive king who wastes the cities is the anti-type of the king who builds the city: &ldquo;I will build my church, and the gates of hell shall not prevail against it&rdquo; (Matt 16:18). Christ is the builder-king whose construction is permanent, contrasted with every Israelite king who proved a destroyer.</p>",
    "8": "<p>A structural note: The nations gathering against the lion-king, catching him in their pit — the international opposition that ends Israel&rsquo;s monarchy. Psalm 2 describes the same international gathering: &ldquo;the kings of the earth set themselves, and the rulers take counsel together, against the LORD and against his Anointed.&rdquo; Christ&rsquo;s trial before Pilate (a Roman ruler) and the Sanhedrin (Israel&rsquo;s leaders) is the ultimate gathering of nations against the LORD&rsquo;s Anointed — fulfilling what Ps 2 predicts and what Ezekiel&rsquo;s lament mourns.</p>",
    "9": "<p>A type: &ldquo;So that his voice would no longer be heard on the mountains of Israel.&rdquo; The silencing of the lion-king&rsquo;s voice is the lament&rsquo;s epitaph. Christ&rsquo;s voice, silenced at the cross, was heard again from the empty tomb — and will be heard one final time when &ldquo;the Lord himself will descend from heaven with a cry of command, with the voice of an archangel, and with the sound of the trumpet of God&rdquo; (1 Thess 4:16). The silenced voice of the Davidic king is not permanently stilled but raised in resurrection proclamation.</p>",
    "10": "<p>A type: &ldquo;Your mother was like a vine transplanted beside the waters.&rdquo; Israel as a fruitful vine points forward to Christ&rsquo;s own vine-identity: &ldquo;I am the true vine&rdquo; (John 15:1). The difference is decisive: Ezekiel&rsquo;s vine is the nation Israel, which fails; Christ is the &ldquo;true&rdquo; (<em>alēthinos</em>) vine — the one in whom all the vine-imagery of the OT is finally and genuinely embodied. The false or failed vines of Ezekiel&rsquo;s laments are the negative context that makes Christ&rsquo;s self-identification as the True Vine intelligible.</p>",
    "11": "<p>A type: &ldquo;She had strong branches that served as rulers&rsquo; scepters.&rdquo; The scepter-branch is the Davidic royal staff (Gen 49:10: &ldquo;the scepter shall not depart from Judah&rdquo;). Christ is the Branch (<em>tsemach</em>, Zech 6:12) and the scepter-rod of Ps 2:9 with which he rules the nations. The strong scepter-branches of the vine represent the Davidic dynasty at its peak; their destruction in the lament creates the expectation for the one indestructible Branch whose rule is eternal.</p>",
    "12": "<p>A type: &ldquo;The east wind dried up her fruit; her strong branches broke and withered; fire consumed them.&rdquo; The east-wind destruction of the vine anticipates the judgment that reaches its climax in the crucifixion: Christ the True Vine is stripped bare, the branches torn off, the vine seemingly destroyed. But &ldquo;unless a grain of wheat falls into the earth and dies, it remains alone; but if it dies, it bears much fruit&rdquo; (John 12:24) — the death of the vine in ch. 19 is the type of the death that produces the harvest of ch. 15 of John.</p>",
    "13": "<p>A type: &ldquo;Now she is planted in the wilderness — in a dry and thirsty land.&rdquo; The vine exiled to the waterless desert is the condition Christ entered in the incarnation: &ldquo;the Son of Man has nowhere to lay his head&rdquo; (Matt 8:20). The wilderness planting of the vine reverses only when the river of life flows from the new temple (Ezek 47:1-12) — which Christ is: the one from whom living water flows (John 7:38-39). The desert exile is temporary; the replanting beside the river of life is permanent.</p>",
    "14": "<p>A type: &ldquo;Fire has spread from one of her own branches and devoured her fruit — she has no strong branch left, no scepter to rule with. This is a lament, and it shall be used as a lament.&rdquo; The lament&rsquo;s climax — no scepter remains — is the OT&rsquo;s honest acknowledgment that the Davidic dynasty&rsquo;s human form has ended. But the lament itself encodes the hope: a lament that prescribes its own future liturgical use anticipates an audience that will sing it with eschatological awareness. Christ turns the lament into a song of triumph: the Lion of Judah holds the scepter that no human king could keep (Rev 5:5).</p>"
  },
  "20": {
    "1": "<p>A structural note: The date formula marks August 591 BCE — a delegation of elders seeking a prophetic oracle from YHWH. Christ is the final and complete answer to all human inquiries after God: &ldquo;long ago, at many times and in many ways, God spoke to our fathers by the prophets, but in these last days he has spoken to us by his Son&rdquo; (Heb 1:1-2). The elders who come to Ezekiel seeking YHWH&rsquo;s word anticipate all who come to Christ, in whom &ldquo;all the treasures of wisdom and knowledge are hidden&rdquo; (Col 2:3).</p>",
    "2": "<p>A structural note: The oracular introduction. Christ is the Word of YHWH come in person — not merely the one who receives and transmits the divine word but the Word itself incarnate (John 1:1, 14). When John says &ldquo;the Word of God&rdquo; he is using the same formula Ezekiel applies to the prophetic word, but identifying its ultimate referent as the eternal Son.</p>",
    "3": "<p>A direct revelation: YHWH refuses to be inquired of by the elders who represent a rebellious people. Christ refuses the sign-seekers who come with wrong hearts: &ldquo;an evil and adulterous generation seeks for a sign&rdquo; (Matt 12:39). The refusal is not indifference but discernment: both YHWH here and Christ in the Gospels refuse to give oracles on demand to those whose inquiry is not grounded in repentance.</p>",
    "4": "<p>A pattern: YHWH commands Ezekiel to pronounce judgment by confronting the elders with their ancestors&rsquo; abominations. Christ pronounces the same kind of judgment in Matt 23: &ldquo;woe to you, scribes and Pharisees... you build the tombs of the prophets and decorate the monuments of the righteous, saying, &lsquo;If we had lived in the days of our fathers, we would not have taken part with them in shedding the blood of the prophets&rsquo;. Thus you witness against yourselves that you are sons of those who murdered the prophets&rdquo; (Matt 23:29-31).</p>",
    "5": "<p>A direct revelation: &ldquo;On the day I chose Israel and swore to the offspring of the house of Jacob, making myself known to them in Egypt.&rdquo; YHWH&rsquo;s election of Israel in Egypt is the type of Christ&rsquo;s election of his own: &ldquo;you did not choose me, but I chose you and appointed you that you should go and bear fruit&rdquo; (John 15:16). The same sovereign, initiating, oath-grounded election that chose Israel from Egypt chooses the disciples in Galilee — and extends the same pattern to all who come to Christ.</p>",
    "6": "<p>A structural note: The promised land &ldquo;flowing with milk and honey, the glory of all lands.&rdquo; The covenant land as the ultimate gift points to the eschatological inheritance Christ secures for his people: &ldquo;blessed are the meek, for they shall inherit the earth&rdquo; (Matt 5:5); the &ldquo;inheritance that is imperishable, undefiled, and unfading, kept in heaven for you&rdquo; (1 Pet 1:4). The land of milk and honey is the temporary OT symbol of the permanent inheritance purchased by Christ.</p>",
    "7": "<p>A structural note: &ldquo;Cast away the detestable things his eyes love, and do not defile yourselves with Egypt&rsquo;s idols.&rdquo; The leaving of Egypt&rsquo;s idols behind as the condition for covenant life is fulfilled in Christ&rsquo;s call: &ldquo;no one can serve two masters&rdquo; (Matt 6:24); &ldquo;little children, keep yourselves from idols&rdquo; (1 John 5:21). The exodus from idolatry is completed in the spiritual exodus Christ effects — not a geographic departure but a heart departure from competing loyalties.</p>",
    "8": "<p>A pattern: The first rebellion — Israel refusing to cast away Egypt&rsquo;s idols. The recurring pattern of hearing YHWH&rsquo;s command and not complying is the condition Christ comes to end by writing the law on the heart (Jer 31:33; 2 Cor 3:3). The inability of hearing to produce obedience is the diagnosis for which the Spirit&rsquo;s inward work is the cure — and Christ mediates this cure through his death and resurrection (Ezek 36:26-27).</p>",
    "9": "<p>A direct revelation: &ldquo;I acted for the sake of my name — that it should not be profaned.&rdquo; The name-theology reaches its fulfillment in Christ, who is the definitive revelation of YHWH&rsquo;s name: &ldquo;I have manifested your name to the people whom you gave me out of the world&rdquo; (John 17:6). The act &ldquo;for the sake of my name&rdquo; that restrained judgment in the exodus is enacted redemptively in Christ: his glorification of the Father&rsquo;s name through the cross is the supreme name-honoring act of history (John 12:28).</p>",
    "10": "<p>A pattern: &ldquo;I brought them out of Egypt and led them into the wilderness.&rdquo; The exodus as the pattern of YHWH&rsquo;s redemption is fulfilled in Christ, who leads the ultimate exodus from sin, death, and the world-system. Jesus discusses his &ldquo;exodus&rdquo; (<em>exodon</em>, Luke 9:31) at the transfiguration with Moses and Elijah — his death and resurrection are the new exodus that the Sinai events typologically anticipated.</p>",
    "11": "<p>A direct revelation: &ldquo;Which, if a person does them, he will live by them.&rdquo; The Torah&rsquo;s principle of life through obedience — cited by Paul in Gal 3:12 and Rom 10:5 — is the standard that makes Christ&rsquo;s perfect obedience redemptively significant. Because Christ alone fulfilled every statute and ordinance perfectly, his righteousness is available for imputation to those who believe: &ldquo;for our sake he made him to be sin who knew no sin, so that in him we might become the righteousness of God&rdquo; (2 Cor 5:21). The life that comes from doing is secured by Christ&rsquo;s doing on behalf of the doers.</p>",
    "12": "<p>A direct revelation: &ldquo;I also gave them my sabbaths as a sign between me and them — so they would know that I am YHWH who sanctifies them.&rdquo; The Sabbath as covenant sign is fulfilled in Christ who is &ldquo;Lord of the Sabbath&rdquo; (Mark 2:28) and who provides the ultimate Sabbath rest: &ldquo;come to me, all who labor and are heavy laden, and I will give you rest&rdquo; (Matt 11:28). The Sabbath rest of Heb 4:9-10 is the eschatological rest into which Christ leads his people — the Sabbath sign pointing to the person who is himself the rest.</p>",
    "13": "<p>A pattern: The first wilderness generation rebels and YHWH threatens to destroy them. The threatened judgment restraint of the wilderness generation is the type of the judgment fully absorbed in Christ. What YHWH threatened (pour out fury, consume in the wilderness) is what Christ bore on the cross — the accumulated fury of all Israel&rsquo;s covenant-breachings poured out on the Son of Man so that the wilderness generation&rsquo;s successors need not be consumed.</p>",
    "14": "<p>A structural note: &ldquo;I acted for the sake of my name — that it not be profaned before the nations.&rdquo; The third occurrence of the name-theology governing YHWH&rsquo;s restraint connects to the cross: Christ&rsquo;s death publicly honored the Father&rsquo;s name before the watching nations. &ldquo;Father, glorify your name&rdquo; (John 12:28) — the cross is the supreme name-glorification, the definitive demonstration that YHWH&rsquo;s character is not mere power but holy love that gives itself to bear judgment for others.</p>",
    "15": "<p>A structural note: The oath not to bring the first generation into the land — because of Sabbath-breaking and idolatry. Christ fulfills what the first generation forfeited: he is the &ldquo;forerunner on our behalf who has entered&rdquo; (Heb 6:20) into the heavenly rest, securing an eternal inheritance for those who could not secure it themselves. The land lost by covenant breach is regained through Christ&rsquo;s perfect faithfulness.</p>",
    "16": "<p>A structural note: &ldquo;Their hearts were set on their idols.&rdquo; The heart-diagnosis — the source of covenant failure — is what Christ comes to address at the deepest level. The new heart of Ezek 36:26 is given by Christ through the Spirit. &ldquo;Keep your heart with all vigilance, for from it flow the springs of life&rdquo; (Prov 4:23); Christ&rsquo;s &ldquo;the pure in heart shall see God&rdquo; (Matt 5:8) is the beatitude that corresponds to the new heart YHWH promises.</p>",
    "17": "<p>A structural note: &ldquo;My eye had pity on them; I did not destroy them.&rdquo; The pity of YHWH that preserves a remnant through judgment is the mercy that culminates in Christ. Paul&rsquo;s &ldquo;because of the great love with which he loved us... made us alive together with Christ&rdquo; (Eph 2:4-5) is the NT version of YHWH&rsquo;s eye of pity that does not consume even the deserving. The mercy that preserves the remnant in the wilderness is the mercy that gives the Son for the world.</p>",
    "18": "<p>A structural note: &ldquo;Do not follow your fathers&rsquo; statutes, do not observe their judgments.&rdquo; The negative commission — leave the fathers&rsquo; corrupt patterns — is completed in Christ&rsquo;s call to leave family loyalties that conflict with kingdom loyalty: &ldquo;do not think that I have come to bring peace to the earth... I have come to set a man against his father&rdquo; (Matt 10:34-35). The new covenant community is not constituted by genealogy or inherited practice but by personal allegiance to the covenant Lord.</p>",
    "19": "<p>A structural note: &ldquo;I am the LORD your God; walk in my statutes, keep my judgments.&rdquo; The positive covenant command is the background for Christ&rsquo;s &ldquo;follow me.&rdquo; Jesus does not merely repeat the command to walk in YHWH&rsquo;s statutes — he personifies the statutes: &ldquo;I am the way, and the truth, and the life&rdquo; (John 14:6). Walking in YHWH&rsquo;s statutes becomes, in the NT, walking with Christ — the law embodied in a person rather than inscribed on tablets.</p>",
    "20": "<p>A direct revelation: &ldquo;Keep my sabbaths holy; they will be a sign between me and you, so you will know that I am the LORD your God.&rdquo; The Sabbath as covenant-identity marker points to Christ as Lord of the Sabbath who fulfills the sign it represents. The Sabbath commanded to the second wilderness generation is the same sign that Jesus reinterprets: not abolished but re-oriented toward himself (&ldquo;the sabbath was made for man, not man for the sabbath. So the Son of Man is lord even of the Sabbath,&rdquo; Mark 2:27-28).</p>",
    "21": "<p>A pattern: The second generation repeats the first generation&rsquo;s rebellion. The structural repetition of human failure across generations is the OT evidence base for Paul&rsquo;s diagnosis: &ldquo;there is none righteous, no, not one&rdquo; (Rom 3:10-12, citing Ps 14:1-3). The universal scope of covenant failure — Egypt, Wilderness 1, Wilderness 2, Canaan — is the empirical foundation for the universality of the atonement: &ldquo;since all have sinned and fall short of the glory of God... they are justified by his grace as a gift, through the redemption that is in Christ Jesus&rdquo; (Rom 3:23-24).</p>",
    "22": "<p>A structural note: YHWH withdraws his hand for the sake of his name before the nations — the third name-restraint. Christ&rsquo;s death and resurrection are the supreme &ldquo;name of YHWH before the nations&rdquo; moment: &ldquo;this Jesus whom you crucified... has been made both Lord and Christ&rdquo; (Acts 2:36). The name-restraint that preserved Israel through the wilderness becomes, at Pentecost, the name-proclamation that gathers people from every nation.</p>",
    "23": "<p>A structural note: The oath of diaspora — the scattering as a consequence of rebellion. The ingathering of the scattered is the eschatological promise that Christ fulfills: &ldquo;I have other sheep that are not of this fold. I must bring them also, and they will listen to my voice. So there will be one flock, one shepherd&rdquo; (John 10:16). The diaspora-oath of Ezek 20:23 is reversed by the gathering-promise of John 10 — Christ gathers what YHWH scattered.</p>",
    "24": "<p>A structural note: The second generation set their eyes on their fathers&rsquo; idols — transgenerational transmission of idolatry. Christ breaks the transgenerational transmission by providing a new genealogy through new birth: &ldquo;what is born of the flesh is flesh, and what is born of the Spirit is spirit&rdquo; (John 3:6). The Spirit&rsquo;s birth does not inherit the fathers&rsquo; idolatry — it constitutes a new lineage from above.</p>",
    "25": "<p>A structural note: &ldquo;I gave them statutes that were not good and judgments by which they could not live&rdquo; — the judicial abandonment to self-destructive religious practice. Paul describes the same pattern in Rom 1:24-28: &ldquo;God gave them up to... dishonoring passions.&rdquo; Christ rescues from this judicial-abandonment condition: &ldquo;the Son of Man came to seek and to save the lost&rdquo; (Luke 19:10) — including those given over to idolatry by divine judgment.</p>",
    "26": "<p>A structural note: The defilement through child sacrifice — YHWH given them over to their worst religious practices. The valley of the son of Hinnom where children were sacrificed becomes <em>gehenna</em> (the word Jesus uses for hell) — the same geography of child-sacrifice is transformed into the metaphor for ultimate judgment. Christ rescues from <em>gehenna</em> precisely by absorbing what <em>gehenna</em> represents: &ldquo;do not fear those who kill the body but cannot kill the soul; rather fear him who can destroy both soul and body in hell&rdquo; (Matt 10:28).</p>",
    "27": "<p>A structural note: Israel blasphemes YHWH through faithlessness in Canaan. The indictment of faithlessness in the promised land connects to Christ&rsquo;s description of the generation that will not repent as &ldquo;an evil and adulterous generation&rdquo; (Matt 12:39) — faithlessness in the presence of the greatest covenant gift (the Messiah himself) is the highest form of the Canaan-blasphemy.</p>",
    "28": "<p>A structural note: Israel&rsquo;s high-place worship in the promised land — offering sacrifices at every green hill. Christ&rsquo;s first temple-cleansing is the definitive judgment on this centuries-old pattern of mislocated worship: worship offered everywhere except where YHWH specified. &ldquo;True worshippers will worship the Father in spirit and truth&rdquo; (John 4:23) replaces both the Jerusalem temple and the Samaritan mountain with Christ himself as the locus of true worship.</p>",
    "29": "<p>A structural note: The ironic naming of the high place — &ldquo;Bamah&rdquo; (&ldquo;what is this high place where you go?&rdquo;). Christ&rsquo;s encounter with the Samaritan woman (John 4:20-24) directly addresses the high-place question: neither this mountain nor Jerusalem is the final worship location — the new place of worship is in Spirit and truth, in Christ himself. The <em>bamah</em> question is answered in the incarnation: worship is now in the person, not the place.</p>",
    "30": "<p>A direct revelation: &ldquo;Are you making yourselves unclean in the same way as your fathers? Do you go whoring after their detestable things?&rdquo; The question confronts the contemporary generation with the pattern of their ancestors. Christ confronts the Pharisees and teachers of the law with the same generational-pattern question: &ldquo;you fill up the measure of your fathers&rdquo; (Matt 23:32). The current generation&rsquo;s rejection of Christ is the filling-to-the-brim of Israel&rsquo;s long history of rejection.</p>",
    "31": "<p>A direct revelation: YHWH refuses to be inquired of while the people continue in idolatry and child sacrifice. Christ&rsquo;s refusal of sign-seekers and his withdrawal from those who seek him for the wrong reasons (John 6:15, 26) is the NT form of this refusal. The God who cannot be instrumentalized — sought for his benefits while his demands are ignored — is the same in both testaments.</p>",
    "32": "<p>A direct revelation: &ldquo;We will be like the nations&rdquo; — the assimilationist aspiration. Christ is YHWH&rsquo;s definitive refusal to allow Israel (or the church) to dissolve into the surrounding culture: &ldquo;you are not of the world, but I chose you out of the world&rdquo; (John 15:19). The distinctiveness YHWH maintained for Israel throughout its history is the pattern of Christ&rsquo;s maintaining the church as a distinct community within the nations — the anti-assimilation principle.</p>",
    "33": "<p>A direct revelation: &ldquo;I will surely reign over you with a mighty hand, an outstretched arm, and outpoured fury.&rdquo; The new exodus with the exodus-vocabulary of mighty hand and outstretched arm now points to Christ&rsquo;s gathering of his scattered people. Paul applies the new-exodus pattern to the Gentile mission: the &ldquo;strong hand and outstretched arm&rdquo; by which YHWH brought Israel from Egypt is the same divine power by which Christ&rsquo;s gospel gathers from every nation (Rom 15:19: &ldquo;by the power of signs and wonders, by the power of the Spirit of God — so that from Jerusalem... I have fulfilled the ministry of the gospel of Christ&rdquo;).</p>",
    "34": "<p>A direct revelation: &ldquo;I will bring you out from the peoples and gather you from the countries where you have been scattered.&rdquo; The gathering of the scattered is Christ&rsquo;s mission: &ldquo;I have other sheep that are not of this fold. I must bring them also&rdquo; (John 10:16); the death of Jesus was &ldquo;to gather into one the children of God who are scattered abroad&rdquo; (John 11:52). The Ezekielian new-ingathering is accomplished by Christ through the cross and the mission of the Spirit.</p>",
    "35": "<p>A structural note: &ldquo;I will bring you into the wilderness of the peoples, and there I will contend with you face to face.&rdquo; The new wilderness encounter with YHWH is fulfilled in Christ&rsquo;s 40-day wilderness testing (Matt 4:1-11) — but Christ passes the test that Israel failed. The new covenant community&rsquo;s formation in the wilderness of persecution and testing is the NT form of this encounter. &ldquo;If anyone would come after me, let him deny himself and take up his cross daily and follow me&rdquo; (Luke 9:23).</p>",
    "36": "<p>A structural note: &ldquo;As I contended with your fathers in the wilderness of Egypt, so I will contend with you.&rdquo; The typological connection between the old and new wilderness contention is the pattern that Hebrews uses throughout (Heb 3:7-4:11): the first wilderness generation is the warning for the church, and Christ is the rest that the wilderness generation forfeited. The new exodus passes through the wilderness of testing into the rest Christ provides.</p>",
    "37": "<p>A direct revelation: &ldquo;I will cause you to pass under the shepherd&rsquo;s rod, and I will bring you into the bond of the covenant.&rdquo; The shepherd&rsquo;s rod that counts the flock is wielded by Christ the Good Shepherd who &ldquo;knows his own&rdquo; (John 10:14) and who will at the last day separate sheep from goats (Matt 25:32). The &ldquo;bond of the covenant&rdquo; (<em>masoret habrit</em>) into which YHWH brings the examined flock is the new covenant sealed by Christ&rsquo;s blood (&ldquo;this cup is the new covenant in my blood,&rdquo; 1 Cor 11:25).</p>",
    "38": "<p>A structural note: &ldquo;I will purge out from among you the rebels and those who sin against me.&rdquo; The eschatological separation — purging rebels from the restored community — is the judgment Christ exercises at the final separation of sheep and goats (Matt 25:31-46). The shepherd&rsquo;s rod that examines the flock leads to the shepherd&rsquo;s final separation: &ldquo;he will separate people one from another as a shepherd separates the sheep from the goats&rdquo; (Matt 25:32).</p>",
    "39": "<p>A structural note: &ldquo;If you will not listen to me, defile my holy name no more with your gifts and your idols.&rdquo; Christ&rsquo;s cleansing of the temple is the definitive enactment of this command: &ldquo;my house shall be called a house of prayer for all the nations, but you have made it a den of robbers&rdquo; (Mark 11:17). The desecration of YHWH&rsquo;s house with commercial activity and corruption is precisely what the temple oracle of ch. 20 protests, and what Jesus judges in John 2 and Mark 11.</p>",
    "40": "<p>A direct revelation: &ldquo;On my holy mountain... there all the house of Israel will serve me... there I will accept them.&rdquo; The eschatological mountain-worship is fulfilled in Christ who is himself the meeting place between YHWH and humanity: &ldquo;destroy this temple, and in three days I will raise it up&rdquo; (John 2:19) — Jesus&rsquo;s body is the temple on the holy mountain, and his resurrection is the establishment of the permanent place of acceptable worship.</p>",
    "41": "<p>A direct revelation: &ldquo;I will accept you as a pleasing aroma when I bring you out from the peoples.&rdquo; The &ldquo;pleasing aroma&rdquo; of the gathered, restored Israel points to Christ, who is himself the acceptable sacrifice and the ground of Israel&rsquo;s acceptance before YHWH. Paul applies the pleasing-aroma language to Christ&rsquo;s self-offering: &ldquo;Christ loved us and gave himself up for us, a fragrant offering and sacrifice to God&rdquo; (Eph 5:2). The gathered people are accepted because they are in Christ who is the acceptable offering.</p>",
    "42": "<p>A structural note: &ldquo;You will know that I am YHWH when I bring you into the land I swore to give to your fathers.&rdquo; The recognition formula on the basis of the land-gift points to the ultimate recognition: &ldquo;every tongue confess that Jesus Christ is Lord, to the glory of God the Father&rdquo; (Phil 2:11). The land-gift recognition in the OT becomes the universal recognition of Christ as YHWH at the consummation.</p>",
    "43": "<p>A structural note: &ldquo;There you will remember your ways and all your deeds by which you defiled yourselves; and you will loathe yourselves for all the evils you have done.&rdquo; Post-restoration shame is the NT pattern of genuine repentance that follows rather than precedes grace: &ldquo;we love because he first loved us&rdquo; (1 John 4:19). The shame that comes after the experience of grace — not as ongoing condemnation but as proper moral understanding — is the pattern of Paul&rsquo;s &ldquo;wretched man that I am&rdquo; (Rom 7:24) spoken by the one who has already been delivered by Christ.</p>",
    "44": "<p>A direct revelation: &ldquo;You will know that I am YHWH when I have dealt with you for my name&rsquo;s sake and not according to your evil ways.&rdquo; YHWH acts for his name&rsquo;s sake, not according to the people&rsquo;s merit — the theological ground of grace, not merit-based restoration. The cross is the supreme demonstration of this principle: &ldquo;God shows his love for us in that while we were still sinners, Christ died for us&rdquo; (Rom 5:8). The restoration comes before moral improvement, grounded entirely in divine grace and the divine name&rsquo;s honor.</p>",
    "45": "<p>A structural note: A new oracle begins — the Negev forest oracle. The transitional formula introduces a new prophetic word within the same chapter. Christ&rsquo;s final discourse (John 13-17) similarly transitions from moral instruction to prophetic disclosure within a single evening — the oracular pattern of consecutive divine words addressing different aspects of the one judgment-and-redemption reality.</p>",
    "46": "<p>A structural note: &ldquo;Set your face toward the south, speak toward the south, and prophesy against the forest of the Negev.&rdquo; The prophetic body-orientation toward the Negev — south of Judah, toward the direction of coming invasion — is the prophetic enactment of directional judgment. Christ&rsquo;s face set toward Jerusalem (&ldquo;he set his face to go to Jerusalem,&rdquo; Luke 9:51, using the same set-face language as Isa 50:7) is the definitive prophetic orientation: he turns toward the place of judgment to absorb it.</p>",
    "47": "<p>A structural note: &ldquo;I will kindle a fire in you that will consume every green tree and every dry tree; the blazing flame will not be quenched.&rdquo; The unquenchable fire of divine judgment — consuming indiscriminately — is what Christ warns of (Mark 9:43: &ldquo;the fire that never will be quenched&rdquo;) and what he absorbs on behalf of those who belong to him. The Negev fire that cannot be put out by human means is extinguished only when it is poured on the one who bears it without being destroyed by it (the burning bush: the fire that burns but does not consume, Exod 3:2-3 — the type of Christ bearing judgment).</p>",
    "48": "<p>A structural note: &ldquo;All flesh will see that I the LORD have lit this fire; it will not be quenched.&rdquo; The universal witness to YHWH&rsquo;s fire-judgment anticipates the universal witness to Christ&rsquo;s cross: &ldquo;and I, when I am lifted up from the earth, will draw all people to myself&rdquo; (John 12:32). The fire that all flesh will see YHWH has lit is transformed into the cross that draws all people to the lifted-up Son of Man.</p>",
    "49": "<p>A pattern: &ldquo;They are saying of me: Is he not just speaking in parables?&rdquo; Ezekiel&rsquo;s complaint that his audience dismisses his oracles as mere stories is the prophetic pattern of Christ&rsquo;s similar reception. Jesus&rsquo;s disciples ask &ldquo;why do you speak to them in parables?&rdquo; (Matt 13:10) and Jesus explains that parables reveal to some and conceal to others (Matt 13:11-15). The prophet dismissed as a spinner of parables is the type of the teacher whose parables are the keys to the kingdom for those with ears to hear.</p>"
  },
  "34": {
    "11": "<p>A direct revelation: 'For thus says the Lord GOD: Behold I, I myself will search for my sheep and seek them out ... I will rescue them from all places where they have been scattered ... I will seek the lost and I will bring back the strayed and I will bind up the injured and I will strengthen the weak.' Jesus's 'I am the good shepherd' (John 10:11) and the parable of the lost sheep (Luke 15:4-6) are the incarnational enactment of Ezek 34's promise. What YHWH said he himself would do (in contrast to the failed shepherds of Israel's leaders) is what Jesus does: the divine shepherd-promise is fulfilled by the Son who is YHWH present in person, doing what YHWH promised he personally would do for the scattered flock.</p>"
  },
  "36": {
    "27": "<p>A direct revelation: 'And I will put my Spirit within you and cause you to walk in my statutes and be careful to obey my rules.' Pentecost is Ezekiel 36:27 enacted. The Spirit's indwelling is not merely motivational but causally efficacious: 'I will cause you to walk' — the Hebrew Hiphil form makes YHWH the enabling cause of the obedience that follows. This is the new covenant's answer to the old covenant's demand without the enabling Spirit: the same Torah-standard now fulfilled because the Spirit from within enables what the law from without could only command. Paul's 'the righteous requirement of the law might be fulfilled in us who walk not according to the flesh but according to the Spirit' (Rom 8:4) is the Christological-pneumatological fulfillment of Ezek 36:27.</p>"
  },
  "47": {
    "9": "<p>A type: 'And wherever the river goes, every living creature that swarms will live, and there will be very many fish. For this water goes there, that the waters of the sea may become fresh; so everything will live where the river goes.' The eschatological temple-river of Ezekiel's vision (ch. 47), increasingly deep and life-giving, is the OT type for the water that flows from Christ. Jesus at Tabernacles (John 7:38-39) applies the Spirit-water promise to himself: 'rivers of living water will flow from within him' — and John explains this is the Spirit. Revelation's new creation river (22:1) flowing from the throne of God and the Lamb completes the Ezekiel type: the new temple's river is Christ himself, and all who drink from him live.</p>"
  }
}

